│  **Financial health assessment (150–200 words)**                                                                     │
│  AMD’s financial profile looks **Strong**. The company returned to solid top-line expansion in 2024, posting         │
│  **$25.8B in revenue, up 14%**, driven by strength in data center and client processors. Profitability also          │
│  improved materially versus the prior year, with **$1.9B in operating income**, **~7.4% operating margin**, and      │
│  **$1.6B in net income**, showing that growth is increasingly flowing through to earnings. While AMD’s margins       │
│  remain well below the very top tier of semiconductor peers, the trend is clearly improving.                         │
│                                                                                                                      │
│  Balance sheet health is a major positive. AMD ended 2024 with about **$5.1B in cash and short-term investments      │
│  versus $1.7B in long-term debt**, giving it a **net cash position** and ample flexibility to fund R&D, AI product   │
│  expansion, and cyclical volatility. The latest quarterly release also suggests momentum continued into 2025, with   │
│  **Q1 revenue of $7.4B** and healthy profitability.                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                      │
│  The main watchpoints are execution in AI/data center, competition with Nvidia and Intel, and cyclicality in         │
│  gaming/embedded markets. Still, AMD currently combines growth, profitability, and balance sheet strength better     │
