│  strategically decisive than data center AI.                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                      │
│  AMD’s most important initiatives are clearly its AI infrastructure stack: Instinct accelerators, Helios rack-scale  │
│  systems, the ZT Systems integration, and ROCm software. Together, these show AMD shifting from a component          │
│  supplier to a more complete AI platform company. That matters because the competitive battleground in AI is moving  │
│  from standalone chips to integrated systems, software, and deployable clusters. EPYC remains strategically          │
│  important as the stable profit and platform anchor underneath the AI push, while Ryzen AI broadens optionality but  │
│  is secondary today. Overall, AMD appears to be **on offense**, not defense: it is launching new products,           │
│  expanding up the stack, and investing to close ecosystem gaps rather than simply protecting share. The main risk    │
│  is execution—especially whether ROCm maturity and system integration can narrow Nvidia’s lead fast enough. Still,   │
│  AMD’s current direction shows stronger ambition and better strategic coherence than a year ago. **Momentum rating:  │
│  Accelerating.**                                                                                                     │
